Differentiate term‐by‐term:

\[
\frac{d}{dx}\frac1{(1-x)^2}
=\frac{d}{dx}\sum_{n=0}^\infty (n+1)x^n
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\frac{2}{(1-x)^3}
=\sum_{n=0}^\infty (n+1)n\,x^{n-1}.
\]

Re‐index by setting \(m=n-1\) in the sum on the right (so \(n=m+1\)):

\[
\frac{2}{(1-x)^3}
=\sum_{m=-1}^\infty (m+2)(m+1)\,x^m
=\sum_{m=0}^\infty (m+2)(m+1)\,x^m,
\]

where the \(m=-1\) term vanishes.  Hence for \(|x|<1\)

\[
\boxed{
\frac{2}{(1-x)^3}
=\sum_{n=0}^\infty (n+1)(n+2)\,x^n.
}
\]
